Ten of the 11 countries adopting the euro dropped their interest rate to 3 percent.
It's rate was 3.9 percent in November down from 5 percent a year before.
Duisenberg has said growth in the euro area countries next year will be about 2.5 percent, lower than the 3 percent predicted earlier.
In Germany, the biggest economy in the future euro-zone, central bankers cut the key interest rate to 3 percent from 3.3 percent.
Austria made the smallest cut, from 3.2 percent.
The year 1999 is the official start-up date of the euro, the common European currency that will unite 11 countries monetarily.
Rates before the cuts had varied throughout the future currency zone, from 3.69 percent in Ireland to 3.2 percent in Austria.
